Midgaard's institutional position on the Eccentric Woodland is managed denial: the city acknowledges it as a known hazard south of the gate, maintains pass checks and route advisories to reduce liability, and avoids full intervention because sustained control would require forces diverted from Roc Road, northern forest routes, and threshold security. Patrol reports since the Lantern Reforms record path drift, contradictory witness accounts, and landmarks that could not be re-located in follow-up inspections — each filed as routine "variance events." Ledgerhouse records show a persistent mismatch between Southern Wild Gate departures and documented returns. The False Escort Syndicate — operating forged gate-pass seals to lure caravans onto dead-end routes — consumed significant Ledgerhouse investigative resources in the last decade without producing prosecutions. Midgaard's refusal of the three Rakuen annexation petitions explicitly cited woodland route instability as the reason administrative integration was impractical, while simultaneously refusing to fund the corridor stabilization that would have made integration feasible. The Honest Ledger movement calls this the Southern Maintenance Paradox. The woodland demonstrates what Midgaard's governance model cannot do: order sustained where it cannot be seen, counted, and reinforced at boundary points. Midgaard's response is bureaucratic — keep the gate records clean, classify interior incidents as variance, and maintain plausible continuity of governance at the edge.

