Rivennid ecological reading of the Eccentric Woodland identifies it as a disconnected fragment lacking root-network coordination. The Great Northern Forest's distributed intelligence does not extend south to this woodland; the Verdant root-network's capacity for directed path behavior, selective environmental response, and ecological regulation operates only where the network is intact. The Eccentric Woodland's shifting paths and unstable clearings reflect the absence of coordinating ecological intelligence, not the presence of directed hostility. The woodland responds to local disturbances without the larger regulatory structure that makes forest behavior readable to those trained in root-network ecology. The pre-institutional bell-walker tradition — navigation by relationship to specific trees and hollows — was a human approximation of Rivennid ecological reading practice, functional precisely because it respected local ecological particularity rather than imposing survey-grid logic. Midgaard's governance failure in the woodland is legible to Rivennid analysis as the failure to maintain those ecological relationships after institutionalization replaced them with posted notices and patrol rotations.

