Umbral analysis of the Eccentric Woodland centers on what is structurally absent: no stable witness network, no consistent record-keeping, no reliable documentation of what occurs inside. The woodland's use by oath-bound gatherings outside temple supervision and by activities institutions preferred not to put in central ledgers reflects the operational value of jurisdictional shadow — not supernatural darkness but institutional illegibility. The False Escort Syndicate, informal dueling circuits, and predator bands operating under ritualized performance all exploit the same structural gap: the woodland is close enough to Midgaard to be accessible and far enough outside its registry to be undocumented. Umbral practitioners in Midgaard use the woodland as a transitional space for activities requiring distance from registry, not because the woodland offers protection — it does not — but because its illegibility makes documentation difficult without institutional commitment that Midgaard has refused to make.
